      <head>Trude (Gertrude) Schiff [Kost]</head>
      <div>

        <p>Daughter of <ref cRef="entity-006733">Louis Schiff</ref> and Hermine (<hi rend="italic"
            >née</hi> Hahn), hence a niece of <ref cRef="entity-000771">Jeanette Schenker</ref>.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <p>The only mention of Trude in the letters of <ref cRef="entity-000781">Anna Schiff</ref>
          states that she was “already officially engaged [to be married]” in 1925 (<ref
            type="correspondence" cRef="OJ-14-8_1">OJ 14/8, [1]</ref>). She is referred to in three
          letters from <ref cRef="entity-000944">Rosa</ref> and <ref cRef="entity-000943">Arnold
            Weil</ref> to Jeanette Schenker: <ref type="correspondence" cRef="OJ-14-10_3">OJ 14/10,
            [3]</ref>, November 20, 1932, <ref type="correspondence" cRef="OJ-14-10_4">OJ 14/10,
            [4]</ref>, January 9, 1933, and <ref type="correspondence" cRef="OJ-14-10_5">OJ 14/10,
            [5]</ref>, April 19, 1933), as being involved in giving assistance to <ref
            cRef="entity-003244">Klara Hatschek</ref> over the latter's illness.</p>

        <p>Trude married Jindřich (Heinrich) Kost, and the couple had a daughter, Ruth. Trude was
          deported to <ref cRef="entity-007493">Auschwitz</ref>, where she died sometime after
          October 9, 1944; nothing is known of the fate of her husband, but Ruth died in <ref
            cRef="entity-007493">Auschwitz</ref> at the same time as her mother.</p>

        <p>Trude Schiff is not mentioned in <ref cRef="entity-000632">Heinrich</ref>’s diary. She is
          not to be confused with <ref cRef="entity-000415">Trude Kaff</ref>, <ref
            cRef="entity-000473">Trude Kral</ref> (pupils of Henrich), or <ref cRef="entity-006282"
            >Trude Kahn</ref>.</p>
      </div>
